{
  "Which of the following is considered a renewable energy source?": "",
  "Natural gas": "",
  "Coal": "",
  "Solar power": "",
  "Petroleum": "",
  "Solar power is renewable because the sun continuously produces energy on a human timescale, unlike fossil fuels which take millions of years to form.": "",
  "What is the primary advantage of wind energy over fossil fuels?": "",
  "Wind energy produces no greenhouse gas emissions during operation": "",
  "Wind turbines are cheaper to build than coal plants": "",
  "Wind turbines produce no waste products at all": "",
  "Wind energy is available everywhere equally": "",
  "Once installed, wind turbines generate electricity without burning fuel and therefore produce no carbon dioxide or other greenhouse gases during operation.": "",
  "Which type of renewable energy harnesses heat from Earth's interior?": "",
  "Biomass energy": "",
  "Tidal energy": "",
  "Hydroelectric power": "",
  "Geothermal energy": "",
  "Geothermal energy taps into the heat generated by radioactive decay and residual heat within Earth's core and mantle, providing a continuous energy source.": "",
  "How do photovoltaic cells generate electricity?": "",
  "By heating water to produce steam": "",
  "By converting sunlight directly into electrical current": "",
  "By burning silicon wafers": "",
  "By reflecting sunlight onto mirrors": "",
  "Photovoltaic cells use semiconductor materials like silicon to convert photons from sunlight directly into an electric current through the photovoltaic effect.": "",
  "What is a major environmental concern associated with large hydroelectric dams?": "",
  "Air pollution from combustion": "",
  "Production of radioactive waste": "",
  "Depletion of water from the water cycle": "",
  "Disruption of river ecosystems and fish migration": "",
  "Large dams block fish migration routes, alter downstream water flow and temperature, flood habitats, and can trap sediment that ecosystems depend on.": "",
  "Which country leads the world in installed wind power capacity?": "",
  "China": "",
  "India": "",
  "United States": "",
  "Germany": "",
  "China has the world's largest installed wind power capacity, having invested heavily in wind farm development as part of its renewable energy expansion strategy.": "",
  "What is biomass energy derived from?": "",
  "Ocean waves and currents": "",
  "Underground mineral deposits": "",
  "Volcanic rock formations": "",
  "Organic materials such as wood, crops, and animal waste": "",
  "Biomass energy comes from organic matter including wood, agricultural residues, animal manure, and dedicated energy crops that store chemical energy from photosynthesis.": "",
  "What factor most limits the reliability of solar and wind energy?": "",
  "Shortage of construction materials": "",
  "High fuel costs": "",
  "Toxic emissions during operation": "",
  "Intermittency due to weather and time of day": "",
  "Solar and wind are intermittent energy sources because their output depends on weather conditions, season, and time of day, requiring energy storage or backup systems.": "",
  "Which renewable source generates electricity from the gravitational pull of the moon and sun on ocean water?": "",
  "Wave energy": "",
  "Tidal energy captures the kinetic energy of rising and falling tides, which are driven primarily by the gravitational forces exerted by the moon and, to a lesser extent, the sun.": "",
  "What is the main purpose of a solar thermal power plant?": "",
  "To convert sunlight directly into electricity using semiconductors": "",
  "To store solar energy in chemical batteries": "",
  "To desalinate seawater using solar radiation": "",
  "To use concentrated sunlight to heat a fluid and drive a turbine": "",
  "Solar thermal power plants use mirrors or lenses to concentrate sunlight, heating a fluid to produce steam that spins a turbine to generate electricity.": "",
  "What is passive solar design?": "",
  "A building technique that uses photovoltaic panels on rooftops": "",
  "An architectural approach that captures and distributes solar energy without mechanical devices": "",
  "A method of cooling buildings using solar-powered air conditioners": "",
  "A system that tracks the sun with motorized mirrors": "",
  "Passive solar design uses building orientation, window placement, thermal mass, and natural ventilation to capture and distribute solar heat without pumps, fans, or other mechanical systems.": "",
  "What is net metering?": "",
  "A tax on carbon emissions from power plants": "",
  "A technique for measuring the total energy output of a wind farm": "",
  "A policy that allows homeowners with solar panels to sell excess electricity back to the grid": "",
  "A method for calculating the efficiency of a geothermal plant": "",
  "Net metering is a billing arrangement that credits solar energy system owners for the electricity they add to the grid, allowing their meter to effectively run backward when they produce more than they consume.": "",
  "What is capacity factor in the context of renewable energy?": "",
  "The total cost of building a renewable energy facility": "",
  "The ratio of actual energy output to the maximum possible output over a period of time": "",
  "The maximum number of turbines that can fit in a wind farm": "",
  "The percentage of a country's energy that comes from renewable sources": "",
  "Capacity factor measures how much energy a power plant actually produces compared to its theoretical maximum, reflecting real-world performance including downtime and variable conditions.": "",
  "What is energy return on investment (EROI)?": "",
  "The profit margin earned by energy companies": "",
  "The percentage of government funding allocated to energy research": "",
  "The speed at which an energy investment pays for itself financially": "",
  "The ratio of energy delivered by a source to the energy required to obtain it": "",
  "EROI compares the usable energy gained from a resource to the total energy invested in extracting and processing it. A higher EROI means a more energy-efficient source.": "",
  "What is a wind turbine's cut-in speed?": "",
  "The speed at which the turbine reaches peak efficiency": "",
  "The minimum wind speed required for the turbine to begin generating electricity": "",
  "The average wind speed at a given location over a year": "",
  "The maximum wind speed at which the turbine can safely operate": "",
  "Cut-in speed is the minimum wind velocity needed to overcome a turbine's inertia and start producing usable power, typically around 3 to 4 meters per second for modern turbines.": "",
  "What does the term 'grid parity' mean?": "",
  "The equal distribution of electricity across all regions of a country": "",
  "The balance between energy supply and demand on the electrical grid": "",
  "The point at which a renewable energy source generates electricity at a cost equal to or less than conventional sources": "",
  "The moment when a power grid reaches its maximum capacity": "",
  "Grid parity occurs when the levelized cost of electricity from a renewable source equals or falls below the cost of electricity from the existing grid, making renewables economically competitive without subsidies.": "",
  "What is a pumped-storage hydroelectric system?": "",
  "A pipeline that delivers water from rivers to solar thermal plants": "",
  "A system that moves water between two reservoirs at different elevations to store and release energy": "",
  "A dam that only generates power during rainy seasons": "",
  "A method of using ocean water to cool nuclear reactors": "",
  "Pumped-storage hydroelectricity stores energy by pumping water uphill to a reservoir during periods of low demand, then releasing it through turbines to generate electricity during peak demand.": "",
  "What is meant by 'distributed generation'?": "",
  "Electricity generation from many small, decentralized sources near the point of use": "",
  "The process of distributing electricity through high-voltage transmission lines": "",
  "A government program that distributes energy subsidies to low-income families": "",
  "The practice of building large power plants in remote locations": "",
  "Distributed generation refers to producing electricity at or near where it will be used, such as rooftop solar panels or small wind turbines, rather than relying solely on large centralized power plants.": "",
  "What is a feed-in tariff?": "",
  "A tax on imported fossil fuels": "",
  "A penalty for power plants that exceed emission limits": "",
  "A government policy that guarantees a fixed price for renewable energy fed into the grid": "",
  "A fee charged to consumers for connecting to the electrical grid": "",
  "A feed-in tariff is a policy mechanism that offers renewable energy producers a guaranteed above-market price for electricity they generate, incentivizing investment in renewable technologies.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'levelized cost of energy' (LCOE)?": "",
  "The price of electricity at the retail level": "",
  "The cost to connect a power plant to the national grid": "",
  "The average cost per unit of electricity over the lifetime of a generating asset": "",
  "The subsidy required to make renewable energy profitable": "",
  "LCOE represents the average net present cost of electricity generation over a facility's entire lifetime, accounting for capital costs, fuel, maintenance, and financing divided by total energy produced.": "",
  "A coastal town is considering building an offshore wind farm to power 10,000 homes. Residents are concerned about the impact on local fisheries and bird populations. Which approach best addresses both energy needs and environmental concerns?": "",
  "Conduct an environmental impact assessment and site turbines to avoid critical habitats and migration routes": "",
  "Cancel the project entirely and continue using fossil fuels": "",
  "Replace the wind farm with a coal power plant built inland": "",
  "Build the wind farm without environmental assessments to save money": "",
  "An environmental impact assessment identifies sensitive areas for wildlife, allowing turbine placement that minimizes harm to bird flyways and fishing grounds while still meeting the town's clean energy goals.": "",
  "A farmer in the Midwest has 200 acres of marginal cropland that produces low yields. An energy company offers to lease the land for a solar farm. What is the most significant environmental trade-off the farmer should consider?": "",
  "Solar panels will contaminate the soil with heavy metals": "",
  "Loss of agricultural land and potential habitat fragmentation versus clean energy production": "",
  "The solar farm will increase local air pollution": "",
  "The solar farm will deplete the local water supply": "",
  "Converting farmland to solar arrays involves a land-use trade-off between food production and clean energy generation. However, since the land is marginal, the trade-off may be favorable, and agrivoltaics can sometimes combine both uses.": "",
  "A developing nation has abundant geothermal resources near an active volcanic region. The government wants to build a geothermal power plant, but local communities worry about land subsidence and water contamination. What is the best course of action?": "",
  "Abandon geothermal energy and invest in imported coal instead": "",
  "Build the plant without community consultation to expedite construction": "",
  "Only operate the plant during dry seasons when water contamination risk is lower": "",
  "Use closed-loop geothermal systems that reinject fluids to minimize subsidence and contamination risks": "",
  "Closed-loop geothermal systems reinject extracted fluids back underground, significantly reducing the risk of land subsidence and preventing contamination of surface and groundwater resources.": "",
  "A city experiences frequent blackouts because its grid relies entirely on solar energy. During a week of overcast weather, power outages disrupt hospitals and schools. What infrastructure improvement would most effectively solve this problem?": "",
  "Rationing electricity use during cloudy periods": "",
  "Adding grid-scale battery storage and diversifying with other renewable sources like wind or geothermal": "",
  "Switching entirely to nuclear power": "",
  "Installing more solar panels to compensate for cloudy days": "",
  "Battery storage systems can store excess solar energy from sunny days for use during cloudy periods, and diversifying the energy mix with other renewables reduces dependence on any single intermittent source.": "",
  "A rural village in sub-Saharan Africa currently has no electricity. The nearest power grid is 150 kilometers away. Which renewable energy strategy would be most practical and cost-effective for providing electricity to this community?": "",
  "Import diesel generators and fuel from the capital city": "",
  "Construct a large hydroelectric dam on the nearest river": "",
  "Build transmission lines to connect to the distant grid": "",
  "Install a small-scale solar microgrid with battery storage": "",
  "A solar microgrid with battery storage is ideal for remote communities because it provides decentralized power without the enormous cost of extending transmission infrastructure over 150 kilometers.": "",
  "An island nation generates 90% of its electricity from imported diesel fuel. The government wants to transition to renewable energy within 15 years. Given the island's tropical climate and consistent trade winds, which combination of renewable sources would be most effective?": "",
  "Biomass from imported wood pellets": "",
  "Large-scale hydroelectric dams": "",
  "Geothermal and tidal power only": "",
  "Solar and wind power with battery storage": "",
  "A tropical island with consistent trade winds is ideally suited for a solar-wind hybrid system. Battery storage addresses intermittency, and the complementary nature of solar and wind (wind often blows at night) provides more consistent power.": "",
  "A state government passes legislation requiring utilities to generate 50% of their electricity from renewable sources by 2035. A utility company currently generates 15% from renewables. Which strategy represents the most realistic path to compliance?": "",
  "Convert all existing coal plants to biomass overnight": "",
  "Phase in new wind and solar installations gradually while retiring aging fossil fuel plants": "",
  "Purchase renewable energy credits from other states without building any new capacity": "",
  "Wait until 2034 and then rapidly build all needed capacity in one year": "",
  "A phased approach allows the utility to steadily increase renewable capacity while managing costs, grid integration challenges, and workforce transitions as older fossil fuel plants reach retirement age.": "",
  "A hydroelectric dam built 40 years ago on a major river has caused significant ecological damage downstream, including loss of salmon runs and coastal erosion from trapped sediment. Environmental groups are calling for dam removal. What factor should policymakers weigh most carefully?": "",
  "The aesthetic appearance of the river valley": "",
  "Whether the dam was originally profitable to build": "",
  "The political popularity of the environmental groups": "",
  "The dam's carbon-free electricity generation versus the ecological benefits of a free-flowing river": "",
  "Policymakers must balance the dam's contribution to clean energy against the ecological restoration that dam removal would provide, including recovering fish populations, restoring sediment flow, and reviving downstream ecosystems.": "",
  "A homeowner installs a 10-kilowatt rooftop solar system in a region that receives an average of 5 peak sun hours per day. The household uses 30 kWh of electricity daily. Based on these figures, how well does the solar system meet the household's needs?": "",
  "The system produces about 5 kWh per day, meeting only one-sixth of demand": "",
  "The system produces about 50 kWh per day, far exceeding demand": "",
  "The system produces about 10 kWh per day, meeting only one-third of demand": "",
  "The system produces about 30 kWh per day, exactly meeting demand": "",
  "A 10 kW system receiving 5 peak sun hours produces approximately 50 kWh per day (10 kW x 5 hours). This exceeds the household's 30 kWh daily consumption, with surplus energy available for net metering.": "",
  "A large wind farm is proposed for a mountain ridge that serves as a major migration corridor for raptors. The project would generate enough clean energy to power 50,000 homes. What mitigation strategy best balances energy production with wildlife conservation?": "",
  "Cancel the project permanently": "",
  "Proceed with construction and ignore wildlife concerns": "",
  "Paint the turbines green so birds cannot see them": "",
